[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You should be dialing keys, not IPs. It\'s a simple, if strange, idea, really. But, we think it\'s the right extraction for the entire future of the internet. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; IP addresses can break without warning, and it\'s completely outside of your'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'device\'s control. Now, keys, on the other hand, those are created by you. They stay the same as your device moves, and are yours to throw away or keep for as long as you need. We think this is how the internet should work, and that\'s why I wrote exists. [music] And today, we\'re delighted to'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'announce that Iro has reached its first major version, 1.0. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; We may be declaring our first stable release, but this project has grown significantly over the 65 releases that'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'led to 1.0. Iro is already used all over the place. The public relays that we run have seen more than 200 million endpoints created in the last 30 days alone.'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Developers are using Iro to stream video, train large language models, talk to agents, secure chats, play games, send files, and many more things that we could jam into this one list. Iro is a fundamental technology aimed at a'

[01:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fundamental shift in the internet, &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; and it\'s already running on millions of devices today. After more than 4 years of building in the open, we have a foundation that we\'re proud [music] of. We ended up building our own implementation of quick'

[01:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'multipath, so Iro can build and manage multiple routes with the same connection, and hot swap paths as conditions change. We have added our own spin on natural reversal within quick, so that we can establish direct connections while keeping connection details encrypted.'

[01:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We added full local-first configurations, so Iro can find and connect to local devices even without internet access. We built and continually check that Iro can compile to WASM and run in the'

[01:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'browser. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; We worked with power users to add hooks, so you can inject logic to control how connections should work. We\'ve even added support for custom transports, so you can use things like Bluetooth low energy, long-range Wi-Fi, or even Tor to'

[01:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'build connections. Iro connections are also far more efficient. [music] It\'s completely normal to see 98% of data transferred in a connection passing directly between devices.'

[02:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Going direct means fewer hops through the cloud, which lowers your egress bill. It\'s also fewer hops through routers, which means the internet gets more efficient overall. With 1.0, in addition to our reference Rust implementation,'

[02:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'re adding official support for Python, Node.js, Swift, and Kotlin, opening up entire new worlds of connectivity. Version 1.0 is not just an API assertion, it also asserts wire stability, which means 1.0 nodes can'

[02:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'talk to each other across any of those sets of languages, &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; literally connecting languages together. For that reason alone, we think the future of the project couldn\'t be brighter. Truly, the internet should be built on dialing keys, on connections'

[02:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that just work, on connections that are secure and default to being direct. With 1.0, you now have a mature networking stack that you can put in your app with confidence. That means now is the time to come build on Iro, and we cannot wait'

[02:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to see what you come up with.'
